\title{Outliers}
\author{Fayssal A.}


\begin{document}

\frame{\titlepage}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Outliers}
Outliers needs close inspection else it can result in wildly wrong estimations.
Outlier is an observation that appears far away and diveges from an overall pattern in a sample.
Values that are very different in magnitude from the others in the feature or target space are called outliers.
Noise and Outliers can lead to inconsistencies (i.e similar or identical features vectors with much different target values)
\begin{itemize}{Outliers types}
    \item[$\bullet$] Univariate:\\
        -Can be found when we look at distribution of a single variable

    \item[$\bullet$] Multivariate:\\
        -Can be found when we look at distributions in multi-dimensions
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}



\begin{frame}
\frametitles{Outliers causes}

Non natural:
\begin{enumerate}
        \item Human errors, errors caused during data collection, recording or entry can cause outliers in data
        \item Measurment error, when the measurement instrument used turns out to be faulty
        \item Intentional error, when human under report an action (i.e alcohol consumption...)
        \item Data pocessing error, when we extract data from multiple sources some manipulation or extraction may lead to outliers in the dataset
        \item Sampling error, when we mix two separate population
\end{enumerate}

%    -Natural: %       -When outlier is not artificial
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Outliers Impact}
\begin{enumerate}
        \item Can drastically change the results of the data analysis and statistical modeling
        \item Increases variance error and reduces the power of statistical tests
        \item Non-randomly distributed outliers can decrease normality
        \item Bias or influence estimated with substantive interest
        \item Impact basic assumption in regression models
\end{enumerate}
\end{frame}


\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Outliers Detection}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item Box-plot, Histogram, scatter plot
    \item Cook Distance (is used only for MLR)
    \item Replace Outliers with missing values and try to predict it

\end{enumerate}
\end{frame}






\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Rule of thumb}
\begin{enumerate}
        \item Lower & Upper 1.5*IQR whisker
        \item Use capping methods, value out of range of 5th and 95t percentile can be considered outlier
        \item Data points, three or more standard deviation away from mean are considered outlier
        \item Taking the log of a predictor or target variable is useful when there are outliers that can't be filtered out because they are important to the model
\end{enumerate}
\end{frame}


\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Box-Plot}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item Simple graphical distribution of a probability distribution (maps a feature value to the probability occurence)
    \item Box-plot are constructed using interquartile
\end{enumerate}

\end{frame}



\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Interquartile Range}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item Often used to find outliers in data
    \item Difference between Q3 and Q1
    \item Q3 and Q1 repsents medians
\end{enumerate}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item Q1 is median of n smallest values
    \item Q3 is median of n largest values
    \item Q2 is ordinary median
\end{enumerate}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item Observation with lower 1.5xIQR whisker, are identified as outliers.\\
        - All values less then Q1-1.5 x IQR are outliers.

    \item Observation with upper 1.5xIQR whisker, are identified as outliers.\\
        - All values more then Q3 + 1.5 x IQR are outliers.

\end{enumerate}

\end{frame}




\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Cook Distance}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item Only used in MLR
    \item Computes the effect of deleting a given observation
    \item Represents the sum of all the changes in the regression model when observation "i" is removed from it
            \begin{equation*}
                D_i = \frac{\sum_{j=1}^{n}(\hat y_j - \hat y_{j(i)})^2}{p (MSE)^2}
            \end{equation*}
            where p is the number of predictors.
    \item Cut-off values to use for spotting highly influential points.
\end{enumerate}

Cut-off values
\end{frame}



\begin{frame}
\frametitle{What to do with outliers?}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item Leave dataset noisy
    \item Delete outliers
    \item "Fix" the records
\end{enumerate}


What strategy to choose depends on
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Knowledge about this domain
    \item Goals of the model
    \item How numerous the anomalies are
    \item What we see in individual record with anomalous values
\end{enumerate}

\end{frame}



